X-----------------------------------------
Xnroff (TOS, Minix) v0.99 BETA 2/26/90 wjr
X-----------------------------------------
X
XThis is an improved release of a version of nroff for both Minix and the
XatariST. It was written under TOS and 4BSD unix but should port easily to
XMinix ST as well. Unfortunately I have no access to Minix (hopefully
Xsomeone did test this before sending it out...ast?).
X
XMuch of this works. The things that (still) don't are all the hard things:
Xdiversions, traps, conditionals, etc. See the man pages for what is not
Xsupported (yet). Font switching, underlining, etc. are limited to reverse
Xvideo on the screen, though stdout will contain underlines as "_^H" for
Xprinters.
X
XThere is a crude man package included (tmac.an) which is still not right
Xbut is better and needs diversions to become right. It should handle most
Xcommon man tasks, though. It gets installed in /usr/lib/tmac under Minix
Xunless you change the location in nroff.h. For testing, you can
X
X	% setenv TMACDIR .
X	% nroff -man file
X
Xto use tmac.an (say) in the cwd.
X
XFor porting info, look in nroff.h and the makefile. The termcap library
Xis used to get standout capabilites for doing bold and italics to the
Xscreen. Minix and BSD have termcap(3) and S5R3 has terminfo, which I
Xbelieve also includes the tgetent/tgetnum/tgetflag/tgetstr functions for
Xcompatibility.
X
XIf you want to try and use nroff for printer output, the termcap library
Xlooks for TERMCAP in your environment (a file) so that you could do:
X
X	% env TERMCAP=printfile nroff -man file
X
Xand substitute your own file with so (standout) for your printer. This
Xassumes your system has env, but you get the idea.
X
XThe program is small enough to work under Minix. It does not have a large
Xstack, but does store all macros and strings in a common namespace. Look
Xin nroff.h for the size.
X
XIf you do hack away, I would appreciate you sending me the changes
Xso I can keep this centralized.
X
XThe future holds increased capabilites, though I find it pretty useful
Xas it is. Most man things are possible and you can do reports and resumes
Xand such without much problem. See the example files included (ex[12].nr).
X
X-Bill Rosenkranz
Xrosenkra@hall.cray.com
/
